paragraphs.text:
%md
Transfer learning is a commonly used in deep learning where pre-trained models are used as the starting point on computer vision and natural language processing tasks for feature extraction or fine-tuning.

In this notebook, we will use Analytics Zoo high-level transfer learning APIs to load a pre-trained Inception_V1 model; freeze its first few layers, replace the classifier on the top, and then fine tune the whole model using Spark DataFrames. We illustrate how to use the fine-tuned model to solve the dogs-vs-cats classification problem.

msg.data:
Transfer learning is a commonly used in deep learning where pre-trained models are used as the starting point on computer vision and natural language processing tasks for feature extraction or fine-tuning.

In this notebook, we will use Analytics Zoo high-level transfer learning APIs to load a pre-trained Inception_V1 model; freeze its first few layers, replace the classifier on the top, and then fine tune the whole model using Spark DataFrames. We illustrate how to use the fine-tuned model to solve the dogs-vs-cats classification problem.

paragraphs.text:
%md
We first download and extract the dataset of cats and dogs. The whole dataset is from https://www.kaggle.com/c/dogs-vs-cats. Here we only take around 1100 images of both cats and dogs for fine tuning.

We also download the pre-trained Inception_V1 model released by Analytics Zoo. Alternatively, you may also download pre-trained Caffe, TensorFlow or Keras model if you wish.

%pyspark
import re

from pyspark.ml import Pipeline
from pyspark.sql.functions import col, udf
from pyspark.sql.types import DoubleType, StringType

from bigdl.nn.criterion import CrossEntropyCriterion
from zoo.common.nncontext import init_nncontext
from zoo.feature.image import *
from zoo.feature.common import ChainedPreprocessing
from zoo.pipeline.api.keras.layers import Dense, Input, Flatten
from zoo.pipeline.api.keras.models import Model
from zoo.pipeline.api.net import Net
from zoo.pipeline.nnframes import NNImageReader, NNClassifier

model_path = 'file:///tmp/analytics-zoo_inception-v1_imagenet_0.1.0.model'
image_path = 'file:///tmp/dogs-vs-cats/*/*'

sc = init_nncontext("Image Transfer Learning Example")

%md
## Data Preparation

Read cats and dogs as a Spark DataFrame using NNImageReader.

%pyspark

imageDF = NNImageReader.readImages(image_path, sc)

%md
Assign label 1.0 to cat and 2.0 to dog. Split the whole DataFrame into training and validation DataFrames.

msg.data: Assign label 1.0 to cat and 2.0 to dog. Split the whole DataFrame into training and validation DataFrames.

paragraphs.text:
%pyspark
getName = udf(lambda row:
                  re.search(r'(cat|dog)\.([\d]*)\.jpg', row[0], re.IGNORECASE).group(0),
                  StringType())
getLabel = udf(lambda name: 1.0 if name.startswith('cat') else 2.0, DoubleType())

labelDF = imageDF.withColumn("name", getName(col("image"))) \
        .withColumn("label", getLabel(col('name')))
(trainingDF, validationDF) = labelDF.randomSplit([0.9, 0.1])
labelDF.select("name","label").show(10)

We then freeze some layers from the very beginning. Here we freeze the layers from input to 'pool4/3x3_s2' inclusive.

model.freeze_up_to(["pool4/3x3_s2"])

%md
Finally, we add a classification layer to classify two classes (namely cat and dog) to the end of the model.

msg.data: Finally, we add a classification layer to classify two classes (namely cat and dog) to the end of the model.

paragraphs.text:
%pyspark
inputNode = Input(name="input", shape=(3, 224, 224))
inception = model.to_keras()(inputNode)
flatten = Flatten()(inception)
logits = Dense(2)(flatten)
lrModel = Model(inputNode, logits)

%md
We define an NNClassifier in Analytics Zoo, which extends org.apache.spark.ml.Estimator and supports training an Analytics Zoo deep learning model with Spark DataFrame data and further integrates it into a standard Spark ML Pipeline.

msg.data: We define an NNClassifier in Analytics Zoo, which extends org.apache.spark.ml.Estimator and supports training an Analytics Zoo deep learning model with Spark DataFrame data and further integrates it into a standard Spark ML Pipeline.

paragraphs.text:
%pyspark
classifier = NNClassifier(lrModel, CrossEntropyCriterion(), transformer) \
        .setLearningRate(0.003).setBatchSize(40).setMaxEpoch(1).setFeaturesCol("image") \
        .setCachingSample(False)
pipeline = Pipeline(stages=[classifier])
